    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hydrogen peroxide can be used as an ear cleaning method, but it's not a decision to be taken lightly. If you choose to use it, make sure to use a very small amount—about 10 drops should suffice. Mix it with warm water to create a solution and then gently place a few drops into your ear. Keep the solution in for a few minutes, then tilt your head to drain it. It's important to be cautious and not to insert anything into your ear canal beyond the outer ear, as this can lead to injury or infection. However, if you're feeling particularly anxious about the blockage, I strongly recommend against using hydrogen peroxide and instead opt for the saline drops I mentioned earlier. They are less risky and still effective at clearing blockages. If you're still unsure, it's always best to consult with a healthcare professional. Remember, I'm here to help you with any questions you might have, but your safety is my top priority.",
